snippet.textOriginal:
​@Zero Crimson 
We were checking into a hotel and it was pretty late, so they gave my father the room key and he went up to open the room.
In 1936, the NYCO and Fifth Avenue were placed under common ownership.
After a strike in 1962, the entire Fifth Avenue system was transferred to the newly formed Manhattan and Bronx Surface Transit Operating Authority on March 22, 1962.
When he opened the door he found two girls huddled in the back of the room! They were terrified because they thought my father was breaking in.
Last year, my family went on a vacation in Maine. They only included classic works by Karl Marx, Friedrich Engels, Vladimir Lenin, and Joseph Stalin, books written by Mao Zedong and Lu Xun, a few political readings, and Revolutionary opera books.
“I had a softball tournament in Virginia Beach when I was in high school." But I missed the flight. The alarm went off for hours before I was finally able to get some sleep…on the floor.
The team was flying down, but we had to book separate flights.

I like to think that most people are rational enough to talk like this. 
      Before the internet we all lived our lives influenced by our immediate surrounding. When I was young, growing up in the midwest, places like California and Florida were like far away lands.  All we ever saw was out immediate culture with TV and music to bring in something from elsewhere.  
     Now, with the explosion in technology the world is not as small for us and what we thought made us significant was not that important any more.  
     We are still reeling from a culture shock folks.  We need to just cowboy up, get a grip on the reins, and hold on for the ride.  And everybody just quit fucking complaining for one god damn moment in your miserable lives.
